window.__QUIZ_DATA__=[{"id":"objective>Biology>2001>1","subject":"Biology","year":"2001","type":"Objective","topic":"CONCEPT OF LIVING : CELL STRUCTURE AND FUNCTIONS OF CELL COMPONENTS.","question":"which of the following indictes that Euglena is a plant?","images":[],"options":{"A":"cospicuous 'eye' spot","B":"presence of gullet","C":"limited movement","D":"presence of starch grains"},"answer":"D","explanation":"Euglena is a unique organism that shows characteristics of both plants and animals. The presence of starch grains in Euglena indicates that it is a plant because starch is a carbohydrate storage product found in plants. Euglena can photosynthesize like plants and store the resulting glucose as starch.","marks":"1","difficulty":"1"},{"id":"objective>Biology>2001>2","subject":"Biology","year":"2001","type":"Objective","topic":"CONCEPT OF LIVING : TISSUES AND SUPPORTING SYSTEMS","question":"Which of the following is a tissue?","images":[],"options":{"A":"volvox","B":"chlamydomonas","C":"epidermis","D":"paramecium"},"answer":"C","explanation":"A tissue is a group of cells that work together to perform a specific function. In this case, the epidermis is a type of tissue. It is the outermost layer of cells that covers an organism, for example, it is the outermost layer of the skin in animals. On the other hand, Volvox and Chlamydomonas are types of green algae, and Paramecium is a type of single-celled organism (protozoan), none of which are tissues.","marks":"1","difficulty":"1"},{"id":"objective>Biology>2001>3","subject":"Biology","year":"2001","type":"Objective","topic":"CONCEPT OF LIVING : CELL STRUCTURE AND FUNCTIONS OF CELL COMPONENTS.","question":"Use the diagram below to answer questions      The structure that produces ATP is labelled","images":["data:image/jpeg;base64,"],"options":{"A":"VII","B":"V","C":"VI","D":"I"},"answer":"A","explanation":"Label VII corresponds to the mitochondrion, recognizable by its distinct oval shape and internal structure. The mitochondrion (labelled VII) is the powerhouse of the cell, where cellular respiration occurs, and ATP is generated through the process of oxidative phosphorylation.","marks":"1","difficulty":"2"},{"id":"objective>Biology>2001>4","subject":"Biology","year":"2001","type":"Objective","topic":"CONCEPT OF LIVING : CELL STRUCTURE AND FUNCTIONS OF CELL COMPONENTS.","question":"Use the diagram below to answer questions    The structure labelled V is the","images":["data:image/jpeg;base64,"],"options":{"A":"cell wall","B":"nucleus","C":"endoplasmic reticulum","D":"mitochondrion"},"answer":"A","explanation":"Based on the provided diagram, label V is situated towards the cell's perimeter, which suggests it is a part of the cell's boundary structure. Given its location and appearance: The correct answer is cell wall. Label V corresponds to the thick outer boundary, characteristic of a cell wall, which provides structural support and protection to plant cells.","marks":"1","difficulty":"2"},{"id":"objective>Biology>2001>5","subject":"Biology","year":"2001","type":"Objective","topic":"CONCEPT OF LIVING : CELL STRUCTURE AND FUNCTIONS OF CELL COMPONENTS.","question":"The major function of the cell membrane is that it","images":[],"options":{"A":"delimits the cytoplasm","B":"synthesize protein","C":"breaks down worn-out organelles","D":"is the site for photosynthesis"},"answer":"A","explanation":"Cell membrane helps to regulate the passage of substance in and out of the cells, hence it can be said to be delimit the cytoplasm  Delimit this marks the limit of something, or fix the limit of something   The cytoplasmic /cell membrane hence fix or determines the limites of cytoplasm","marks":"1","difficulty":"1"},{"id":"objective>Biology>2001>6","subject":"Biology","year":"2001","type":"Objective","topic":"CONCEPT OF LIVING : PROPERTIES AND FUNCTIONS OF THE LIVING CELL","question":"carbonhydrates are stored in the animals cell in the form of","images":[],"options":{"A":"starch","B":"glycogen","C":"plastid","D":"maltose"},"answer":"B","explanation":"In animals, carbohydrates are stored in the form of glycogen. Glycogen is a polysaccharide that the body can easily convert back into glucose when needed for energy. Starch is the form in which plants store carbohydrates, not animals. Plastids are organelles found in plant cells, not a form of carbohydrate storage. Maltose is a type of sugar, not a storage form of carbohydrates.","marks":"1","difficulty":"1"},{"id":"objective>Biology>2001>7","subject":"Biology","year":"2001","type":"Objective","topic":"CONCEPT OF LIVING : THE CELL AND ITS ENVIRONMENT","question":"A piece of yam weighing 1.0gm was put into some salt solution. After 3 hours, it removed and weighed. the recorded weight was 1.2 gms. The simple experiment demonstrates that the","images":[],"options":{"A":"salt solution is more concentrated that the cell sap of the yam","B":"cell sap of the yam is more concentrated than salt solution","C":"salt solution has same concentration as the cell sap of the yam","D":"the yam lost some water molecules to the salt soution"},"answer":"B","explanation":"The yam gained weight after being placed in the salt solution, which indicates that water molecules moved from the salt solution into the yam. This is a process known as osmosis, where water molecules move from an area of lower concentration to an area of higher concentration. In this case, the cell sap of the yam must have been more concentrated than the salt solution, causing water to move into the yam to try and balance the concentrations. Therefore, the correct answer is that the cell sap of the yam is more concentrated than the salt solution.","marks":"1","difficulty":"2"},{"id":"objective>Biology>2001>8","subject":"Biology","year":"2001","type":"Objective","topic":"CONCEPT OF LIVING : THE CELL AND ITS ENVIRONMENT","question":"A major reason why red blood cell can survive in the blood is that the","images":[],"options":{"A":"blood plasma and red blood cell are isotonic","B":"red blood cells are hypotonic to the plasma","C":"the red blood cell are hypotonic to the blood plasma","D":"te red blood cells recieve digested nutrients"},"answer":"A","explanation":"Red blood cells can survive in the blood because the blood plasma and red blood cells are isotonic. This means that the concentration of solutes is the same inside and outside the cells, which prevents water from moving across the cell membrane by osmosis. If the red blood cells were hypotonic to the plasma, they would take in too much water and burst. On the other hand, if they were hypertonic, they would lose water and shrink. Therefore, isotonic conditions are necessary for the survival of red blood cells.","marks":"1","difficulty":"2"},{"id":"objective>Biology>2001>9","subject":"Biology","year":"2001","type":"Objective","topic":"BASIC ECOLOGICAL CONCEPTS : ECOLOGICAL FACTORS","question":"Which of the following phenomena affects plants growth in an alkaline soil?","images":[],"options":{"A":"excessive plasmolysis","B":"excessive transpiration","C":"Excessive sunlight","D":"poor drainage"},"answer":"D","explanation":"Acidity or alkalinity of the soil can cause water logging and the poor drainage of th soil.","marks":"1","difficulty":"2"},{"id":"objective>Biology>2001>10","subject":"Biology","year":"2001","type":"Objective","topic":"CONCEPT OF LIVING : THE CELL AND ITS ENVIRONMENT","question":"A red blood cell haemolyses when placed in the hypotonic solution because","images":[],"options":{"A":"it contains haemoglobin","B":"the cytoplasm is less dense","C":"the cell lack a wall","D":"is pigment has a high affinity for water"},"answer":"D","explanation":"RBC hemolyses when placed in the hypotonic solution because its pigment has a high affinity for water. Hemoglobin, the protein in red blood cells that carries oxygen, has a high affinity for water. When an RBC is placed in a hypotonic solution, water rushes into the cell to equalize the concentration. Hemoglobin's high affinity for water means that it will absorb water, causing the cell to swell and eventually burst (hemolyze).","marks":"1","difficulty":"2"},{"id":"objective>Biology>2001>11","subject":"Biology","year":"2001","type":"Objective","topic":"CONCEPT OF LIVING : CELL STRUCTURE AND FUNCTIONS OF CELL COMPONENTS.","question":"Which of the following structures are visible in the cell of a plant during mitosis?","images":[],"options":{"A":"centrioles, chromatids and molecules","B":"Homologous , chromosomes, nuclear membrane and spindle fibre","C":"cell wall, centrioles and chromatids","D":"chromosomes, nuclear membrane and centromere"},"answer":"D","explanation":"During mitosis, the chromosomes, nuclear membrane, and centromere are visible in a plant cell. The chromosomes condense and become visible, the nuclear membrane dissolves to allow the chromosomes to separate, and the centromere is the part of the chromosome where the spindle fibers attach to pull the chromosomes apart. - Chromosomes are indeed visible during mitosis (as sister chromatids).  - Nuclear membrane is visible, although it breaks down and reforms.  - Centromere is a region on the chromosome that becomes visible during mitosis, specifically during metaphase.    Other options are incorrect:   Centrioles, chromatids, and nucleolus:  - Centrioles are not found in plant cells.  - Nucleolus is not typically visible during mitosis.  Homologous chromosomes, nuclear membrane, and spindle fibers:  - Homologous chromosomes are not visible during mitosis (they're paired up during meiosis).  Cell wall, centrioles, and chromatids:  - Centrioles are not found in plant cells.","marks":"1","difficulty":"3"},{"id":"objective>Biology>2001>12","subject":"Biology","year":"2001","type":"Objective","topic":"ADAPTATION FOR SURVIVAL AND EVOLUTION : BEHAVIOURAL ADAPTATIONS IN SOCIAL ANIMALS.","question":"Display is a phenomenon which occurs when animal is","images":[],"options":{"A":"ready for mating","B":"fighting to defend itself","C":"approaching puberty","D":"chasing away an intruder"},"answer":"A","explanation":"Display in animals is a set of complex behaviors, such as visual signals, sounds, and movements, that are used primarily to attract a mate. Therefore, it occurs when an animal is ready for mating.","marks":"1","difficulty":"1"},{"id":"objective>Biology>2001>13","subject":"Biology","year":"2001","type":"Objective","topic":"CONCEPT OF LIVING : REPRODUCTION","question":"The advantages of sexual reproduction include following except","images":[],"options":{"A":"it allows the formation of new species","B":"it allow production of desirable traits","C":"it permits variation of individuals","D":"it provides means for the variation of chromosomes number from generation to generation"},"answer":"D","explanation":"Sexual reproduction does not provide a means for the variation of chromosome number from generation to generation. The number of chromosomes in a species remains constant from generation to generation due to sexual reproduction. This is because during sexual reproduction, the gametes (sperm and egg cells) undergo a special type of cell division called meiosis, which ensures that the number of chromosomes is halved. Therefore, when the sperm and egg combine during fertilization, the original number of chromosomes is restored. This ensures that the number of chromosomes remains constant from one generation to the next.","marks":"1","difficulty":"2"},{"id":"objective>Biology>2001>14","subject":"Biology","year":"2001","type":"Objective","topic":"CONCEPT OF LIVING : TISSUES AND SUPPORTING SYSTEMS","question":"Which of the following groups contains a non-supporting structure in animals","images":[],"options":{"A":"cartilage, bone and pseudopodia","B":"pellicle, chitin and bone","C":"humerus,ribs and cartilage","D":"fermur, pellicle and chitin"},"answer":"B","explanation":"The correct answer is 'pellicle, chitin and bone'. In this option, pellicle is a non-supporting structure in animals. Pellicle is a thin layer supporting the cell membrane in various protozoa. It provides protection but does not provide structural support like bones or cartilage. Chitin and bone, on the other hand, are supporting structures. Chitin is a long-chain polymer of a N-acetylglucosamine, a derivative of glucose, and is found in many places throughout the natural world. It is a characteristic component of the cell walls of fungi, the exoskeletons of arthropods such as crustaceans and insects, the radulae of mollusks, and the beaks and internal shells of cephalopods. Bone is a rigid organ that constitutes part of the vertebrate skeleton in animals. Bones protect the various organs of the body, produce red and white blood cells, store minerals, provide structure and support for the body, and enable mobility.","marks":"1","difficulty":"2"},{"id":"objective>Biology>2001>15","subject":"Biology","year":"2001","type":"Objective","topic":"BIOLOGY OF HEREDITY (GENETICS) : GENETIC TERMINOLOGIES","question":"Which of the following statement is true about blood grouping?","images":[],"options":{"A":"Group AB can denote blood to all groups","B":"Group O are universal recipients","C":"Group A has A antigen in its plasma","D":"Group O has no antigen"},"answer":"D","explanation":"Blood group O has neither A nor B antigens on the surface of the red blood cells but does have both A and B antibodies in the blood plasma.","marks":"1","difficulty":"2"},{"id":"objective>Biology>2001>16","subject":"Biology","year":"2001","type":"Objective","topic":"CONCEPT OF LIVING : TRANSPORT SYSTEM","question":"Which of the following is not constituent of blood plasma","images":[],"options":{"A":"protein","B":"mineral salt","C":"water","D":"platelet"},"answer":"D","explanation":"Blood plasma is a yellowish liquid component of blood that holds the blood cells in whole blood in suspension. It is the liquid part of the blood that carries cells and proteins throughout the body. It makes up about 55% of the body's total blood volume. It is composed of water (90%), proteins, and mineral salts. Platelets, however, are not a constituent of blood plasma, they are a component of the blood itself. Therefore, the correct answer is 'platelet'.","marks":"1","difficulty":"1"},{"id":"objective>Biology>2001>17","subject":"Biology","year":"2001","type":"Objective","topic":"PLANT AND ANIMAL NUTRITION : PLANT NUTRITION","question":"The process by which plants convey food material to different part of the body is called","images":[],"options":{"A":"nutrition","B":"absorption","C":"circulation","D":"translocation"},"answer":"D","explanation":"The process by which plants convey food material to different parts of the body is called translocation. Translocation in plants is the process where products of photosynthesis (sugar, amino acids, etc.) are transported from 'source' tissues (like leaves) to 'sink' tissues (the parts of the plant where the nutrients are needed or stored). This is different from nutrition (the process of obtaining food necessary for health and growth), absorption (the process by which nutrients are taken up by the plant's roots from the soil), and circulation (a term more commonly used in animal biology to describe the movement of blood through the body).","marks":"1","difficulty":"2"},{"id":"objective>Biology>2001>18","subject":"Biology","year":"2001","type":"Objective","topic":"CONCEPT OF LIVING : RESPIRATORY SYSTEM","question":"Which part of the gill of fish involved in gaseous exchange?","images":[],"options":{"A":"gilt silts","B":"gill bars","C":"gill cover","D":"gill filament"},"answer":"D","explanation":"The gill filament is the part of the gill of fish involved in gaseous exchange. Gaseous exchange in fish occurs through the gill filaments. These are thin structures that have a large surface area to allow for the efficient exchange of gases. Oxygen from the water diffuses into the blood in the gill filaments, while carbon dioxide diffuses out from the blood into the water.","marks":"1","difficulty":"2"},{"id":"objective>Biology>2001>19","subject":"Biology","year":"2001","type":"Objective","topic":"BASIC ECOLOGICAL CONCEPTS : MICROORGANISMS: MAN AND HIS HEALTH.","question":"Which of the following is not a product of fermentation of glucose","images":[],"options":{"A":"Energy","B":"Alcohol","C":"lactic acid","D":"carbon dioxide"},"answer":"A","explanation":"Energy is not a product of the fermentation of glucose but rather a result or outcome of the process. During fermentation, glucose is metabolized to produce substances such as alcohol, lactic acid, and carbon dioxide, depending on the type of fermentation. The energy released during this process is in the form of ATP, which cells use for various functions. However, energy itself is not a substance or product of fermentation.","marks":"1","difficulty":"2"},{"id":"objective>Biology>2001>20","subject":"Biology","year":"2001","type":"Objective","topic":"ADAPTATION FOR SURVIVAL AND EVOLUTION : EVOLUTION","question":"Which of the following pair of structure does not perform similar functions?","images":[],"options":{"A":"lungs and spiracles","B":"Root hair and mammalian hair","C":"feathers and scales","D":"contractile vacuole"},"answer":"B","explanation":"Root hair: a small finger-like projection of cells near the tip of root that are important is mineral uptake   mammalian hair does not function in mineral uptake","marks":"1","difficulty":"2"},{"id":"objective>Biology>2001>21","subject":"Biology","year":"2001","type":"Objective","topic":"CONCEPT OF LIVING : RESPIRATORY SYSTEM","question":"The effect of the contraction of the muscles of the diaphragm is that","images":[],"options":{"A":"The volume of the thoracic cavity increase","B":"more carbon dioxide is expelled through the nostrils","C":"rib cage is drawn inwards","D":"the intercostal muscle becomes relaxed"},"answer":"A","explanation":"The diaphragm is a dome-shaped muscle located at the base of the lungs. When it contracts, it flattens and moves downward, increasing the volume of the thoracic cavity, which allows the lungs to expand and fill with air.","marks":"1","difficulty":"2"},{"id":"objective>Biology>2001>22","subject":"Biology","year":"2001","type":"Objective","topic":"CONCEPT OF LIVING : EXCRETORY SYSTEMS","question":"Which of the following is an excretory product of Amoeba?","images":[],"options":{"A":"urea","B":"Ammonia","C":"uric acid","D":"amino acid"},"answer":"B","explanation":"Amoeba, being a unicellular organism, excretes waste products directly into the environment by the process of diffusion. The primary excretory product of Amoeba is Ammonia. Ammonia is a nitrogenous waste product formed due to the metabolism of proteins. It is highly soluble in water and is toxic. Therefore, it needs to be eliminated from the body quickly. In the case of Amoeba, it diffuses out of the cell into the surrounding water.","marks":"1","difficulty":"1"},{"id":"objective>Biology>2001>23","subject":"Biology","year":"2001","type":"Objective","topic":"CONCEPT OF LIVING : REGULATION OF INTERNAL ENVIRONMENT (HOMEOSTASIS)","question":"Which of the followings processes occurs when the body temperature of mammal rises above the normal?  I. The arterioles in the skin dilate  II. Sweat production is reduced  III. The erector muscles contract","images":[],"options":{"A":"I only","B":"II only","C":"I and III only","D":"II and III only"},"answer":"A","explanation":"Whe the body temperature of a mammal rises above normal, these occur   - The arterioles of the skin dilate  -Sweat production increase  - Erector muscles relax","marks":"1","difficulty":"2"},{"id":"objective>Biology>2001>24","subject":"Biology","year":"2001","type":"Objective","topic":"CONCEPT OF LIVING : EXCRETORY SYSTEMS AND MECHANISMS","question":"The following function are associated with the liver except","images":[],"options":{"A":"regulation of blood sugar","B":"production of heat","C":"production of fibrinogen","D":"production of vitamin D"},"answer":"B","explanation":"The liver is primarily responsible for the following functions:  -\tRegulation of blood sugar: The liver helps maintain blood glucose levels by storing glycogen and releasing glucose as needed.  -\tProduction of fibrinogen: The liver synthesizes fibrinogen, which is an essential protein for blood clotting.  -\tProduction of vitamin: The liver stores and metabolizes various vitamins, including vitamin A, D, E, and K.    However, the production of heat is not a primary function of the liver. While the liver does generate some heat as a byproduct of its metabolic processes, it is not specifically responsible for the regulation or production of heat in the body. This is a function more directly associated with muscle activity and overall metabolism.","marks":"1","difficulty":"2"},{"id":"objective>Biology>2001>25","subject":"Biology","year":"2001","type":"Objective","topic":"CONCEPT OF LIVING : SENSE ORGANS","question":"Short-sight could be corrected with the use of","images":[],"options":{"A":"convex lens","B":"cylindrical lens","C":"concave lens","D":"bifocal lens"},"answer":"C","explanation":"Short-sightedness, also known as myopia, is a common vision condition in which you can see objects near to you clearly, but objects farther away are blurry. It occurs when the shape of your eye causes light rays to bend (refract) incorrectly, focusing the images in front of the retina instead of directly on the retina. A concave lens is used to correct this condition. The lens spreads out the light rays so that they can come to a point further back in the eye, right on the retina. This allows the person to see distant objects clearly.","marks":"1","difficulty":"1"},{"id":"objective>Biology>2001>26","subject":"Biology","year":"2001","type":"Objective","topic":"PLANT AND ANIMAL NUTRITION : PLANT NUTRITION","question":"Which of the following statement about the maize grain is not correct? it","images":[],"options":{"A":"undergoes hypogeal germination","B":"is a fruit","C":"is non-endospermous","D":"has pericarp fused with testa"},"answer":"C","explanation":"Maize is an endospermous seed. In endospermous seeds, the endosperm is retained within the seed and the embryo utilizes the stored food in the endosperm during germination. Other options are correct. Maize undergoes hypogeal germination where the cotyledons remain underground. It is a fruit because in botanical terms, a fruit is the mature ovary of a flower. The pericarp of maize is indeed fused with the testa, forming a structure known as the caryopsis.","marks":"1","difficulty":"2"},{"id":"objective>Biology>2001>27","subject":"Biology","year":"2001","type":"Objective","topic":"CONCEPT OF LIVING : REPRODUCTIVE SYSTEM OF MAMMALS","question":"In mammals, fertilization usually occur in the?","images":[],"options":{"A":"cervix","B":"vagina","C":"uterus","D":"oviduct"},"answer":"D","explanation":"In mammals, fertilization usually occurs in the oviduct, also known as the fallopian tube. This is where the sperm meets the egg. The cervix, vagina, and uterus are parts of the female reproductive system, but they are not the sites of fertilization.","marks":"1","difficulty":"1"},{"id":"objective>Biology>2001>28","subject":"Biology","year":"2001","type":"Objective","topic":"CONCEPT OF LIVING : REPRODUCTION","question":"Which of the following vertebrates incubates their eggs","images":[],"options":{"A":"mammals","B":"birds","C":"amphibians","D":"Reptiles"},"answer":"B","explanation":"Birds are known to incubate their eggs. Incubation refers to the process by which certain oviparous (egg-laying) animals hatch their eggs; it involves the maintenance of the fertile eggs within a certain temperature range for a certain period. Birds do this by sitting on their eggs. Mammals do not lay eggs, with the exception of monotremes like the platypus and echidna. Amphibians and reptiles lay eggs, but they do not typically incubate them in the same way birds do.","marks":"1","difficulty":"1"},{"id":"objective>Biology>2001>29","subject":"Biology","year":"2001","type":"Objective","topic":"PLANT AND ANIMAL NUTRITION : PLANT NUTRITION","question":"Which of the following is an agent of pollination of grasses?","images":[],"options":{"A":"insect","B":"water","C":"wind","D":"mammals"},"answer":"C","explanation":"Grasses are typically pollinated by wind. This type of pollination is known as anemophily. Grasses have light, dry pollen that can be easily carried by the wind. They also have feathery or plumose stigmas to catch the wind-borne pollen. This is why wind is the correct answer and not insects, water, or mammals.","marks":"1","difficulty":"1"},{"id":"objective>Biology>2001>30","subject":"Biology","year":"2001","type":"Objective","topic":"ADAPTATION FOR SURVIVAL AND EVOLUTION : BEHAVIOURAL ADAPTATIONS IN SOCIAL ANIMALS.","question":"The spinnerets found in the caterpillars of butterfly is used for","images":[],"options":{"A":"protection against predators","B":"feeding on vegetation","C":"movement on twigs","D":"production of silk thread"},"answer":"D","explanation":"Spinnerets in caterpillars are specialized organs that are used for the production of silk thread. This silk thread is used by the caterpillar to form a cocoon during its pupal stage. Therefore, the correct answer is 'production of silk thread'.","marks":"1","difficulty":"1"},{"id":"objective>Biology>2001>31","subject":"Biology","year":"2001","type":"Objective","topic":"CONCEPT OF LIVING : CELL STRUCTURE AND FUNCTIONS OF CELL COMPONENTS.","question":"The diagram below is transverse section of a leaf.      carbon dioxide enter the leaf through the structure labelled.","images":["data:image/jpeg;base64,"],"options":{"A":"I","B":"II","C":"IX","D":"X"},"answer":"C","explanation":"\"IX\" corresponds to the air space directly connected to the stoma, it is correct to state that carbon dioxide enters the leaf through the stoma itself, but for practical purposes in the diagram, this might be indicated as the air space","marks":"1","difficulty":"2"},{"id":"objective>Biology>2001>32","subject":"Biology","year":"2001","type":"Objective","topic":"CONCEPT OF LIVING : CELL STRUCTURE AND FUNCTIONS OF CELL COMPONENTS.","question":"The diagram below is transverse section of a leaf.    Manufactured food is transported from the leaves through the structure labelled","images":["data:image/jpeg;base64,"],"options":{"A":"IV","B":"V","C":"VI","D":"VII"},"answer":"B","explanation":"The Part labeled V is the Phloem. Phloem transports organic compounds like sugars, amino acids, and hormones produced by photosynthesis from the leaves to other parts of the plant.","marks":"1","difficulty":"2"},{"id":"objective>Biology>2001>33","subject":"Biology","year":"2001","type":"Objective","topic":"CONCEPT OF LIVING : CELL STRUCTURE AND FUNCTIONS OF CELL COMPONENTS.","question":"The diagram below is transverse section of a leaf.    The pallisade cells are the structure labelled","images":["data:image/jpeg;base64,"],"options":{"A":"III","B":"IV","C":"VI","D":"VIII"},"answer":"A","explanation":"The pallisade cells are the structure labelled III  -\tMesophyll: The inner tissue of the leaf where photosynthesis occurs.  -\tPalisade mesophyll*: The upper layer of mesophyll with tightly packed cells containing chloroplasts.  -\tStomata: Small openings on the underside of the leaf that allow for gas exchange (CO2 in, O2 out).  Others include:   -\tGuard cells: Specialized cells that surround and regulate the stomata.  -\tEpidermis:  The outer layer of the leaf, covering both the upper and lower surfaces.   Cuticle: A thin, waxy layer on the epidermis that prevents water loss.","marks":"1","difficulty":"2"},{"id":"objective>Biology>2001>34","subject":"Biology","year":"2001","type":"Objective","topic":"CONCEPT OF LIVING : CELL STRUCTURE AND FUNCTIONS OF CELL COMPONENTS.","question":"The diagram below is transverse section of a leaf.    which of the groups of structure listed below contains chloroplast?","images":["data:image/jpeg;base64,"],"options":{"A":"I, II and III","B":"II,III and VII","C":"III, VIII and IX","D":"III,VIII and XI"},"answer":"D","explanation":"The structure III, VIII and XI contains chloroplast","marks":"1","difficulty":"2"},{"id":"objective>Biology>2001>35","subject":"Biology","year":"2001","type":"Objective","topic":"BASIC ECOLOGICAL CONCEPTS : ENERGY TRANSFORMATION IN NATURE","question":"In which of the following processes is light energy converted to ATP?","images":[],"options":{"A":"Osmosis","B":"Transpiration","C":"chemosynthesis","D":"photosynthesis"},"answer":"D","explanation":"Photosynthesis is the process by which green plants and some other organisms use sunlight to synthesize foods with the help of chlorophyll pigments. During this process, light energy is converted to ATP (Adenosine Triphosphate), which is a form of energy that cells can use. Therefore, the correct answer is photosynthesis.","marks":"1","difficulty":"1"},{"id":"objective>Biology>2001>36","subject":"Biology","year":"2001","type":"Objective","topic":"BASIC ECOLOGICAL CONCEPTS : ENERGY TRANSFORMATION IN NATURE","question":"The correct equation for photosynthesis is","images":["data:image/png;base64,","data:image/png;base64,","data:image/png;base64,","data:image/png;base64,"],"options":{"A":"","B":"","C":"","D":""},"answer":"C","explanation":"6CO2 + 6H2O---sunlight/chlorophyll\u2192C6H12O6 + 6O2 is the equation for photosynthesis","marks":"1","difficulty":"2"},{"id":"objective>Biology>2001>37","subject":"Biology","year":"2001","type":"Objective","topic":"BASIC ECOLOGICAL CONCEPTS : ENERGY TRANSFORMATION IN NATURE","question":"Which of the following is an evidence of photosynthesis?","images":[],"options":{"A":"Aborption of light","B":"formation of starch","C":"Availabilty of carbon dioxide","D":"splittting of water molecules"},"answer":"B","explanation":"Photosynthesis is a process used by plants and other organisms to convert light energy into chemical energy that can later be released to fuel the organisms' activities. One of the main products of photosynthesis is starch, a carbohydrate that plants use for energy storage. Therefore, the formation of starch is a direct evidence of photosynthesis.","marks":"1","difficulty":"1"},{"id":"objective>Biology>2001>38","subject":"Biology","year":"2001","type":"Objective","topic":"BASIC ECOLOGICAL CONCEPTS : MICROORGANISMS: MAN AND HIS HEALTH.","question":"Which of the following organisms is a chemo-autroph?","images":[],"options":{"A":"Virus","B":"Bacteria","C":"paramecium","D":"Euglena"},"answer":"B","explanation":"Chemoautotrophs are organisms that use inorganic molecules as a source of energy. They are able to make their own food, but unlike plants (which are phototrophs), they do not use sunlight as their energy source. Instead, they use the energy from chemical reactions, often involving inorganic molecules such as hydrogen sulfide or ammonia. Bacteria are a prime example of chemoautotrophs. Viruses, paramecium, and euglena are not chemoautotrophs. Viruses are not even considered living organisms by many scientists. Paramecium and euglena are both types of protists, and they are heterotrophs, not autotrophs.","marks":"1","difficulty":"2"},{"id":"objective>Biology>2001>39","subject":"Biology","year":"2001","type":"Objective","topic":"CONCEPT OF LIVING : CELL STRUCTURE AND FUNCTIONS OF CELL COMPONENTS.","question":"Turgidity in the cell of plant does not easily lead to bursting of the cell because the","images":[],"options":{"A":"cell membrane can resist the turgidity","B":"large vacuole contained in the cell, can continuously take in water","C":"cellulose cell wall can resist the turgidity","D":"cytoplasm is jelly-like"},"answer":"C","explanation":"Turgidity in plant cells does not easily lead to bursting because the cellulose cell wall can resist the turgidity. Turgidity refers to the state of being swollen due to high fluid content. In the context of plant cells, this is often due to water entering the cell by osmosis. The cellulose cell wall of plant cells is rigid and provides structural support, preventing the cell from bursting even when it is turgid.","marks":"1","difficulty":"2"},{"id":"objective>Biology>2001>40","subject":"Biology","year":"2001","type":"Objective","topic":"PLANT AND ANIMAL NUTRITION : PLANT NUTRITION","question":"magnesium is need by plants for","images":[],"options":{"A":"protein synthesis","B":"formulation of cell membrane","C":"activation of enzymes","D":"formation of chlorophyll"},"answer":"D","explanation":"Magnesium is needed by plants for the formation of chlorophyll. Chlorophyll is the pigment that gives plants their green color and is crucial for photosynthesis, the process by which plants convert light energy into chemical energy. Magnesium is a central atom in the chlorophyll molecule, and without it, plants cannot produce chlorophyll.","marks":"1","difficulty":"2"},{"id":"objective>Biology>2001>41","subject":"Biology","year":"2001","type":"Objective","topic":"PLANT AND ANIMAL NUTRITION : PLANT NUTRITION","question":"which of the following is not a micronutrient?","images":[],"options":{"A":"maganese","B":"copper","C":"potassium","D":"zinc"},"answer":"C","explanation":"Micronutrients are nutrients required by organisms in small quantities for proper growth and development. They include vitamins and trace minerals. The options given are all minerals. However, potassium is not a micronutrient but a macronutrient. Macronutrients are nutrients required in larger quantities. They include carbohydrates, proteins, fats, and certain minerals like potassium, nitrogen, and phosphorus. Therefore, potassium is not a micronutrient.","marks":"1","difficulty":"1"},{"id":"objective>Biology>2001>42","subject":"Biology","year":"2001","type":"Objective","topic":"CONSERVATION OF NATURAL RESOURCES : SOIL, WATER, WILDLIFE, FOREST AND MINERALS","question":"loam is the best type of soil for crop production because","images":[],"options":{"A":"it has a high percentage of clay which prevent leaching","B":"it has humus content","C":"it porous and has good-water retention capacity","D":"gravels which obstruct implements are absent from it"},"answer":"B","explanation":"Loam is the best type of soil for ceop production because it has high humus content.","marks":"1","difficulty":"2"},{"id":"objective>Biology>2001>43","subject":"Biology","year":"2001","type":"Objective","topic":"PLANT AND ANIMAL NUTRITION : ANIMAL NUTRITION","question":"The mineral needed for the formlation of haemoglobin is","images":[],"options":{"A":"magnesium","B":"iron","C":"phosphorus","D":"calcium"},"answer":"B","explanation":"Haemoglobin is a protein in red blood cells that carries oxygen throughout the body. Iron is a key component in the formation of haemoglobin. It is the iron in haemoglobin that gives blood its red color. When there is not enough iron, the body can't produce enough of a substance in red blood cells that enables them to carry oxygen (hemoglobin). As a result, iron deficiency anemia may leave you tired and short of breath.","marks":"1","difficulty":"1"},{"id":"objective>Biology>2001>44","subject":"Biology","year":"2001","type":"Objective","topic":"CONCEPT OF LIVING : SENSE ORGANS","question":"A person who fails to detects the bitter taste of a substance swallowed, is more likely to have","images":[],"options":{"A":"dead taste buds on the tongue","B":"avoided the substance from contacting the back of his/her tongue","C":"fewer taste bud on the tongue","D":"swallowed the substance without any water"},"answer":"C","explanation":"The bitter taste sensation is located at the back of the tongue   \"fewer taste buds on the tongue.\" This option suggests that the person may have fewer functional taste buds, which could indeed lead to reduced ability to perceive tastes like bitterness. If a person has fewer taste buds or if their taste buds are not functioning properly (due to reasons such as age, health conditions, or genetic factors), they may have difficulty detecting certain tastes.","marks":"1","difficulty":"2"},{"id":"objective>Biology>2001>45","subject":"Biology","year":"2001","type":"Objective","topic":"BASIC ECOLOGICAL CONCEPTS : FOOD WEBS AND TROPHIC LEVELS","question":"Which of the following solution is suitable for removing chlorophyll in a green leaf?","images":[],"options":{"A":"million reagent","B":"methylated spirit","C":"Benedict solution","D":"fehlings's solution"},"answer":"B","explanation":"Methylated spirit is used to remove chlorophyll from a green leaf. Chlorophyll is the pigment that gives plants their green color and is involved in photosynthesis. Methylated spirit, also known as denatured alcohol, is used in this process because it can dissolve chlorophyll without damaging the leaf's structure. The other options listed, Million's reagent, Benedict's solution, and Fehling's solution, are all used in various chemical tests but are not suitable for removing chlorophyll.","marks":"1","difficulty":"2"},{"id":"objective>Biology>2001>46","subject":"Biology","year":"2001","type":"Objective","topic":"BASIC ECOLOGICAL CONCEPTS : ECOLOGICAL FACTORS","question":"Which of the following is not promoted by wind speed?","images":[],"options":{"A":"Rill erosion","B":"weathering of parent rock","C":"Breeding of plant","D":"opening of stomata"},"answer":"C","explanation":"Wind speed does not promote the breeding of plants. Wind speed can influence erosion, weathering of rocks, and the opening of stomata. Erosion and weathering are physical processes that can be intensified by the force of the wind. The opening of stomata, small openings on the surface of plants, can also be influenced by wind as it can cause the plant to lose water and open its stomata to take in more carbon dioxide for photosynthesis. However, the breeding of plants is a biological process that is not directly influenced by wind speed.","marks":"1","difficulty":"2"},{"id":"objective>Biology>2001>47","subject":"Biology","year":"2001","type":"Objective","topic":"BASIC ECOLOGICAL CONCEPTS : MICROORGANISMS: MAN AND HIS HEALTH.","question":"micro-organism which break down dead organisms and absorb their content are called","images":[],"options":{"A":"decomposers","B":"consumers","C":"parasites","D":"commensals"},"answer":"A","explanation":"Decomposers are organisms that break down dead or decaying organisms, and in doing so, they carry out the natural process of decomposition. Like herbivores and predators, decomposers are heterotrophic, meaning that they use organic substrates to get their energy, carbon and nutrients for growth and development. While the terms decomposer and detritivore are often interchangeably used, detritivores ingest and digest dead matter, while decomposers directly absorb nutrients in a form that can be used by plants and other autotrophs.","marks":"1","difficulty":"1"},{"id":"objective>Biology>2001>48","subject":"Biology","year":"2001","type":"Objective","topic":"BASIC ECOLOGICAL CONCEPTS : NUTRIENT CYCLING IN NATURE","question":"The substance recycled in the soil by the activities of micro-organism during the decay of dead organism are first utilised by the","images":[],"options":{"A":"carnivores","B":"herbivores","C":"scavengers","D":"autotrophs"},"answer":"D","explanation":"The substances recycled in the soil by the activities of micro-organisms during the decay of dead organisms are first utilised by the autotrophs. Autotrophs are organisms that can produce their own food from the substances available in their surroundings using light (photosynthesis) or chemical energy (chemosynthesis). In this case, the substances recycled in the soil serve as nutrients for the autotrophs, which are then passed up the food chain when the autotrophs are consumed by herbivores, and so on.","marks":"1","difficulty":"2"},{"id":"objective>Biology>2001>49","subject":"Biology","year":"2001","type":"Objective","topic":"ECOLOGICAL MANAGEMENT : BIOLOGICAL ASSOCIATIONS","question":"Which of the following associations can upset the balance of nature?","images":[],"options":{"A":"epiphitism","B":"parasitism","C":"symbiosis","D":"saprophytism"},"answer":"B","explanation":"Parasitism can upset the balance of nature. Parasitism is a type of symbiotic relationship between organisms of different species where one organism, the parasite, benefits at the expense of the host. In this relationship, the parasite lives on or in the body of the host. If the number of parasites increases significantly, it can cause harm to the host species, which can upset the balance of nature. Epiphytism, symbiosis, and saprophytism are types of interactions that generally do not upset the balance of nature. Epiphytism is a non-harmful interaction where one plant grows on another. Symbiosis is a mutually beneficial relationship. Saprophytism is a relationship where an organism feeds on dead or decaying organic matter.","marks":"1","difficulty":"2"},{"id":"objective>Biology>2001>50","subject":"Biology","year":"2001","type":"Objective","topic":"ADAPTATION FOR SURVIVAL AND EVOLUTION : BEHAVIOURAL ADAPTATIONS IN SOCIAL ANIMALS.","question":"which of the following groups of factors do the agama lizard compete for?  I. space  II. Food  III. Mates","images":[],"options":{"A":"space and food only","B":"space, food and mate only","C":"food and mates only","D":"space , food and mates"},"answer":"D","explanation":"Agama lizards, like many other species, compete for resources that are essential for their survival and reproduction. These resources include space, food, and mates. Space is needed for shelter and territory, food is necessary for energy and growth, and mates are required for reproduction. Therefore, the correct answer is 'space, food, and mates'.","marks":"1","difficulty":"2"},{"id":"objective>Biology>2001>51","subject":"Biology","year":"2001","type":"Objective","topic":"MICROORGANISMS: MAN AND HEALTH : CARRIERS OF MICROORGANISMS","question":"Which of the following structure in a housefly aids in transmission of disease in man?","images":[],"options":{"A":"Hairs","B":"spiracles","C":"Antennae","D":"wings"},"answer":"A","explanation":"The hairs on a housefly's body can carry pathogens from one place to another, thus aiding in the transmission of diseases in humans. When a housefly lands on a surface, it can pick up bacteria, viruses, and other pathogens on its hairs. When it later lands on food or other surfaces that humans may touch or consume, it can deposit these pathogens, potentially leading to disease transmission. The other options, spiracles, antennae, and wings, do not directly aid in disease transmission. Spiracles are involved in respiration, antennae in sensing the environment, and wings in flight.","marks":"1","difficulty":"2"},{"id":"objective>Biology>2001>52","subject":"Biology","year":"2001","type":"Objective","topic":"MICROORGANISMS: MAN AND HEALTH : CARRIERS OF MICROORGANISMS","question":"Which of the these is not correct about tse-tse fly and mosquito? they","images":[],"options":{"A":"Habour protozoa as disease agents","B":"posses piercing and sucking mouth part","C":"have intermediate host","D":"injects disease-causing organism into the blood stream"},"answer":"C","explanation":"Tse-tse flies and mosquitoes are both vectors for disease, meaning they can transmit disease-causing organisms from one host to another. However, they do not have intermediate hosts. An intermediate host is an organism that supports the immature or nonreproductive forms of a parasite. In the case of these insects, they are the definitive hosts, meaning they are the organisms in which the parasites reach maturity and where sexual reproduction occurs. Therefore, the statement 'have intermediate host' is not correct.","marks":"1","difficulty":"2"},{"id":"objective>Biology>2001>53","subject":"Biology","year":"2001","type":"Objective","topic":"MICROORGANISMS: MAN AND HEALTH : CARRIERS OF MICROORGANISMS","question":"Which of these is a vector of malaria fever?","images":[],"options":{"A":"Female anopheles mosquito","B":"male anopheles mosquito","C":"female culex mosquito","D":"male culex mosquito"},"answer":"A","explanation":"Malaria is transmitted to humans through the bites of infected female Anopheles mosquitoes. They are the primary vectors of malaria. Male mosquitoes do not bite and therefore do not transmit the disease. Culex mosquitoes are not vectors of malaria.","marks":"1","difficulty":"1"},{"id":"objective>Biology>2001>54","subject":"Biology","year":"2001","type":"Objective","topic":"ECOLOGY OF POPULATION : PRESERVATION AND STORAGE OF FOODS","question":"Fresh milk is often kept in-refrigerated vehicles, for distribution to constumers in order to","images":[],"options":{"A":"ensure proper share of fresh milk to all customers","B":"ensure delivery of milk to customer in good time","C":"improve the quality of the milk","D":"ensure that the milk is preserved for a longer period"},"answer":"D","explanation":"Fresh milk is often kept in refrigerated vehicles to ensure that it is preserved for a longer period. Refrigeration slows down the growth of bacteria and other microorganisms that cause milk to spoil. This is not about ensuring proper share, delivery in good time or improving the quality of the milk, but about preserving its existing quality for a longer period.","marks":"1","difficulty":"1"},{"id":"objective>Biology>2001>55","subject":"Biology","year":"2001","type":"Objective","topic":"MICROORGANISMS: MAN AND HEALTH : MICROORGANISMS IN ACTION","question":"In medicine, bacteria have proven very useful due to the production of","images":[],"options":{"A":"nitrate","B":"antibiotics","C":"curred tobacco","D":"tanned leather"},"answer":"B","explanation":"Bacteria are known to produce antibiotics. Antibiotics are substances produced by bacteria and fungi that are capable of killing, or inhibiting the growth of, other microorganisms. This property is used in medicine to treat bacterial infections. The other options listed are not typically associated with bacteria.","marks":"1","difficulty":"1"},{"id":"objective>Biology>2001>56","subject":"Biology","year":"2001","type":"Objective","topic":"VARIATION IN POPULATION : MORPHOLOGICAL VARIATIONS","question":"use the following human charateristic to answer the questions  I. complexion   II. Height  III. Blood RH factor  IV colour blindness    Which of the above human charateristics are discontinuous variation","images":[],"options":{"A":"I and III only","B":"II and III only","C":"II and IV only","D":"III and IV only"},"answer":"D","explanation":"Discontinous variation involves sharp difference between the various form of a given difference.  It often arises as a result of mutation E.g colour blindness, tongue rolling, ability to taste PTC, blood groups e.t.c","marks":"1","difficulty":"2"},{"id":"objective>Biology>2001>57","subject":"Biology","year":"2001","type":"Objective","topic":"VARIATION IN POPULATION : MORPHOLOGICAL VARIATIONS","question":"use the following human charateristic to answer the questions  I. complexion   II. Height  III. Blood RH factor  IV colour blindness  which of the charateristics can be expressed phenotypically?","images":[],"options":{"A":"I and II only","B":"I, II and IV only","C":"I,III and IV only","D":"I, II and III only"},"answer":"A","explanation":"To be expressed phenotypically means they are features that can be observed physically. Hence, height and complexion are expressed physically.","marks":"1","difficulty":"2"},{"id":"objective>Biology>2001>58","subject":"Biology","year":"2001","type":"Objective","topic":"VARIATION IN POPULATION : PHYSIOLOGICAL VARIATIONS","question":"Which of the following variation is applicable to a weight lifter?","images":[],"options":{"A":"Continous variation variation","B":"discontinuous variation","C":"Hereditary variation","D":"Acquired variation"},"answer":"D","explanation":"Weight lifting is a skill that is not inherited but acquired through training and practice. Therefore, the variation in muscle mass and strength that a weight lifter experiences is an acquired variation.","marks":"1","difficulty":"2"},{"id":"objective>Biology>2001>59","subject":"Biology","year":"2001","type":"Objective","topic":"BIOLOGY OF HEREDITY (GENETICS) : GENETIC TERMINOLOGIES","question":"The character that expresses itself in the presence of the contrasting charater is","images":[],"options":{"A":"hybrid","B":"allele","C":"recessive","D":"dominant"},"answer":"D","explanation":"In genetics, the character that expresses itself in the presence of the contrasting character is known as the dominant trait. Dominant traits are those that are expressed or visible when a living organism has at least one copy of the dominant allele. An allele is a variant form of a gene. Some genes have a variety of different forms, which are located at the same position, or genetic locus, on a chromosome. In the given options, 'dominant' is the correct term that describes this genetic concept.","marks":"1","difficulty":"1"},{"id":"objective>Biology>2001>60","subject":"Biology","year":"2001","type":"Objective","topic":"ADAPTATION FOR SURVIVAL AND EVOLUTION : BEHAVIOURAL ADAPTATIONS IN SOCIAL ANIMALS.","question":"Which of the following animals exhibits territoriaity?","images":[],"options":{"A":"bees","B":"Bats","C":"lizard","D":"Rabbits"},"answer":"C","explanation":"Territoriality is a type of intraspecific interaction where an organism or group of organisms defends its territory against others. In the animal kingdom, many species exhibit territorial behavior, including lizards. Lizards are known to establish and defend their territories from other lizards, often through displays of aggression. Bees, bats, and rabbits do not typically exhibit territorial behavior in the same way. Bees live in colonies and share a common area, bats often live in large groups known as colonies, and rabbits are more social animals that live in groups. Therefore, the correct answer is 'lizard'.","marks":"1","difficulty":"1"}];